---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const title = "Captive-Bred African Grey Parrots for Sale | CITES-Documented USA Breeder | CongoAfricanGreys.com";
const description = "Buy captive-bred African Grey parrots with full CITES Appendix II documentation — legally bred in the USA since 2014. Congo $1,700–$3,500, Timneh $1,500–$1,600. USDA AWA licensed breeder, Midland TX.";
const canonical = "https://congoafricangreys.com/captive-bred-african-grey-parrot/";
const ogType = "website";

const schemaJson = JSON.stringify({
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": "Captive-Bred African Grey Parrots: What It Means and Why It Matters",
      "url": "https://congoafricangreys.com/captive-bred-african-grey-parrot/",
      "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "CongoAfricanGreys.com" },
      "publisher": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "CongoAfricanGreys.com",
        "url": "https://congoafricangreys.com/"
      },
      "description": "What captive-bred means for African Grey parrots, why it matters legally and behaviorally, and how to verify a bird's status before purchase."
    },
    {
      "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
      "itemListElement": [
        { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": "https://congoafricangreys.com/" },
        { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Captive-Bred African Grey Parrot", "item": "https://congoafricangreys.com/captive-bred-african-grey-parrot/" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What does captive-bred mean for African Grey parrots?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Captive-bred means the bird was born from parents already in legal captivity in the USA — it has never been wild-caught or illegally imported. Every captive-bred African Grey sold in the USA must have CITES Appendix II documentation proving its legal captive-bred status. Wild-caught African Greys cannot be legally imported into the USA under the Wild Bird Conservation Act of 1992."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Are all African Grey parrots for sale in the USA captive-bred?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Legally, yes — but not every seller follows the law. Wild-caught African Greys are trafficked into the USA illegally through falsified documents. Always demand CITES documentation and verify the breeder's USDA AWA license number before purchasing. If a seller cannot produce both, walk away."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Are captive-bred African Greys better pets than wild-caught?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes, significantly. Captive-bred hand-raised African Greys are socialized to humans from hatching, making them less fearful, more trainable, and more likely to develop talking ability. Wild-caught birds are traumatized by capture and transport, often never fully tame, and frequently carry diseases that can infect other birds in the household."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
});
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} canonical={canonical} ogType={ogType} schemaJson={schemaJson}>

<style>
  :root {
    --green: #2D6A4F;
    --clay: #e8604c;
    --cream: #faf7f4;
    --dark: #1c1a18;
    --muted: #6b6560;
    --border: #ede5dc;
    --green-lt: #eaf4ef;
  }
  .container { max-width: 1200px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 0 24px; }
  .container-text { max-width: 760px; margin: 0 auto; }

  .breadcrumb { font-size: 0.8rem; color: var(--muted); padding: 16px 0 8px; font-family: Sora, sans-serif; }
  .breadcrumb a { color: var(--green); text-decoration: none; }
  .breadcrumb a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }

  .page-hero { background: var(--green); color: #fff; padding: 52px 0 44px; }
  .page-hero h1 { font-family: Lora, serif; font-size: clamp(1.6rem, 3.5vw, 2.5rem); font-weight: 700; margin: 0 0 14px; line-height: 1.2; max-width: 700px; }
  .page-hero .lead { font-family: Sora, sans-serif; font-size: 1.02rem; opacity: 0.9; max-width: 620px; margin: 0; line-height: 1.65; }
  .hero-badge { display: inline-block; background: rgba(255,255,255,0.18); color: #fff; font-family: Sora, sans-serif; font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 0.8px; text-transform: uppercase; padding: 6px 14px; border-radius: 50px; margin-bottom: 16px; }

  /* Trust bar */
  .trust-bar { background: #1e5238; padding: 16px 0; }
  .trust-bar-inner { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 8px 28px; justify-content: center; align-items: center; }
  .trust-item { font-family: Sora, sans-serif; font-size: 0.82rem; font-weight: 600; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.9); letter-spacing: 0.3px; }
  .trust-item::before { content: '✅ '; }

  .content-section { padding: 56px 0; }
  .content-section h2 { font-family: Lora, serif; font-size: 1.65rem; color: var(--green); margin: 0 0 16px; }
  .content-section p { font-family: Sora, sans-serif; font-size: 0.97rem; color: var(--dark); line-height: 1.75; max-width: 70ch; margin: 0 0 16px; }
  .content-section ul { font-family: Sora, sans-serif; font-size: 0.97rem; color: var(--dark); line-height: 1.75; max-width: 68ch; padding-left: 20px; margin: 0 0 20px; }
  .content-section li { margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .internal-link { color: var(--green); font-weight: 600; text-decoration: none; }
  .internal-link:hover { text-decoration: underline; }

  /* Comparison table */
  .comparison-table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 28px 0; font-family: Sora, sans-serif; font-size: 0.9rem; }
  .comparison-table thead th { background: var(--green); color: #fff; padding: 12px 16px; text-align: left; font-weight: 600; }
  .comparison-table thead th:first-child { border-radius: 8px 0 0 0; }
  .comparison-table thead th:last-child { border-radius: 0 8px 0 0; }
  .comparison-table tbody tr:nth-child(even) { background: var(--cream); }
  .comparison-table tbody td { padding: 11px 16px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--dark); line-height: 1.55; }
  .comparison-table tbody td:first-child { font-weight: 600; color: var(--muted); width: 26%; }
  .good { color: #1e5238; font-weight: 600; }
  .bad { color: #b94444; }

  /* Highlight box */
  .highlight-box { background: var(--green-lt); border-left: 4px solid var(--green); border-radius: 0 10px 10px 0; padding: 18px 20px; margin: 24px 0; }
  .highlight-box p { font-family: Sora, sans-serif; font-size: 0.93rem; color: #1c5c40; line-height: 1.65; margin: 0; }

  .section-divider { border: none; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); margin: 48px 0; }

  .faq-section { padding: 48px 0; background: var(--cream); }
  .faq-section h2 { font-family: Lora, serif; font-size: 1.65rem; color: var(--green); margin: 0 0 28px; }
  details { border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; margin-bottom: 12px; background: #fff; }
  summary { font-family: Sora, sans-serif; font-weight: 600; font-size: 0.97rem; padding: 18px 20px; cursor: pointer; list-style: none; color: var(--dark); }
  summary::-webkit-details-marker { display: none; }
  summary::after { content: '+'; float: right; color: var(--clay); font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 400; }
  details[open] summary::after { content: '−'; }
  .faq-body { padding: 0 20px 18px; font-family: Sora, sans-serif; font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--muted); line-height: 1.7; }

  .cta-section { padding: 56px 0; text-align: center; }
  .cta-section h2 { font-family: Lora, serif; font-size: 1.55rem; color: var(--dark); margin: 0 0 12px; }
  .cta-section p { font-family: Sora, sans-serif; color: var(--muted); max-width: 500px; margin: 0 auto 24px; font-size: 0.97rem; line-height: 1.65; }
  .cta-buttons { display: flex; gap: 16px; justify-content: center; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .btn-primary { display: inline-flex; align-items: center; background: var(--clay); color: #fff; font-family: Sora, sans-serif; font-weight: 600; font-size: 0.95rem; padding: 13px 28px; border-radius: 50px; text-decoration: none; transition: background 0.2s; }
  .btn-primary:hover { background: #c94d3a; }
  .btn-outline { display: inline-flex; align-items: center; background: transparent; color: var(--green); border: 2px solid var(--green); font-family: Sora, sans-serif; font-weight: 600; font-size: 0.95rem; padding: 11px 26px; border-radius: 50px; text-decoration: none; transition: background 0.2s, color 0.2s; }
  .btn-outline:hover { background: var(--green); color: #fff; }

  @media (max-width: 767px) {
    .page-hero { padding: 38px 0 32px; }
    .content-section { padding: 40px 0; }
    .comparison-table { font-size: 0.82rem; }
    .comparison-table tbody td { padding: 9px 10px; }
    .trust-bar-inner { gap: 6px 16px; }
  }
</style>

<main id="main-content">

  <div class="container">
    <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <a href="/">Home</a> › Captive-Bred African Grey Parrot
    </nav>
  </div>

  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero-badge">CITES Appendix II · USA Bred</div>
      <h1>Captive-Bred African Grey Parrots: What It Means and Why It Matters</h1>
      <p class="lead">Every African Grey sold legally in the USA must be captive-bred with CITES documentation. Here's what that means, how to verify it, and why it makes a profound difference in the bird you bring home.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="trust-bar">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="trust-bar-inner">
        <span class="trust-item">CITES Appendix II Documented</span>
        <span class="trust-item">USDA AWA Licensed Since 2014</span>
        <span class="trust-item">USA Captive-Bred Only</span>
        <span class="trust-item">DNA Sexed</span>
        <span class="trust-item">Avian Vet Checked</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="content-section">
    <div class="container container-text">

      <h2>What "Captive-Bred" Means for African Greys</h2>
      <p>A captive-bred African Grey was born from parents already living in legal captivity in the United States — in a licensed breeding facility under USDA Animal Welfare Act oversight. The bird has never been wild-caught, never been transported illegally, and carries a <strong>CITES Appendix II certificate</strong> that proves its legal status.</p>
      <p>This distinction is not optional. African Greys (<em>Psittacus erithacus</em>) were uplisted to CITES Appendix I in 2016, and the Wild Bird Conservation Act of 1992 prohibited their commercial importation into the USA long before that. Every legally sold African Grey in the USA today traces its lineage entirely to birds already in captivity before those laws took effect.</p>

      <div class="highlight-box">
        <p><strong>The rule is simple:</strong> If a seller cannot produce a CITES certificate for the specific bird you are buying — not a generic letter, not a "breeder's statement" — walk away. <a href="/cites-african-grey-documentation/" class="internal-link" style="color: #1c5c40;">Learn what CITES documentation looks like</a>.</p>
      </div>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>Captive-Bred vs. Wild-Caught: Why It Matters</h2>
      <p>This comparison isn't academic — it directly affects the bird you live with for the next 40–60 years.</p>

      <table class="comparison-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Category</th>
            <th>Captive-Bred (Legal)</th>
            <th>Wild-Caught (Illegal in USA)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Legal status</td>
            <td class="good">Fully legal with CITES docs</td>
            <td class="bad">Federal crime to import/sell</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Temperament</td>
            <td class="good">Socialized to humans from hatching</td>
            <td class="bad">Fearful, may never fully tame</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Disease risk</td>
            <td class="good">Vet-checked, low risk</td>
            <td class="bad">Can carry Psittacosis, Newcastle disease</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Talking ability</td>
            <td class="good">Develops naturally with socialization</td>
            <td class="bad">Often inhibited by trauma and fear</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Lifespan in captivity</td>
            <td class="good">40–60 years with proper care</td>
            <td class="bad">Significantly reduced due to stress</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Documentation</td>
            <td class="good">CITES certificate + health guarantee</td>
            <td class="bad">Falsified documents or none</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>Why Captive-Bred Birds Bond Better</h2>
      <p>Hand-raised captive-bred African Greys are imprinted on humans during the critical socialization window — the first 12–16 weeks of life. During this window, the bird's brain is actively building the neural pathways that determine what it considers "safe" and "family." A bird raised entirely by humans during this period treats humans as its flock.</p>
      <p>Wild-caught birds missed this window entirely. Their flock imprinting happened with other Greys in the forest canopy. No amount of patient taming can fully replicate what hand-raising achieves in weeks during that critical period.</p>
      <p>This is also why <a href="/how-to-tame-african-grey-parrot/" class="internal-link">taming a captive-bred hand-raised Grey</a> takes weeks, not years.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>How Our Birds Are Bred</h2>
      <p>Mark and Teri Benjamin have been captive-breeding African Grey parrots in Midland, Texas since 2014 under USDA Animal Welfare Act license. Our breeding pairs — both Congo and Timneh — were sourced from established USA captive bloodlines with full CITES traceability.</p>
      <p>Every chick is pulled for hand-feeding at 2–3 weeks and handled daily by multiple family members through the full 12–16 week weaning period. Before placement, each bird receives:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>CITES Appendix II documentation (specific to that individual bird)</li>
        <li>DNA sex certificate from an accredited avian genetics laboratory</li>
        <li>Avian veterinarian health certificate</li>
        <li>Written health guarantee</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Concerned about scams in the African Grey market? Read our guide on <a href="/how-to-avoid-african-grey-parrot-scams/" class="internal-link">how to avoid African Grey parrot scams</a> and verify any breeder before sending a deposit.</p>

    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container container-text">
      <h2>Captive-Bred FAQs</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>What does captive-bred mean for African Grey parrots?</summary>
        <div class="faq-body">Captive-bred means the bird was born from parents already in legal captivity in the USA — it has never been wild-caught or illegally imported. Every captive-bred African Grey sold in the USA must have CITES Appendix II documentation proving its legal captive-bred status. Wild-caught African Greys cannot be legally imported into the USA under the Wild Bird Conservation Act of 1992.</div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Are all African Grey parrots for sale in the USA captive-bred?</summary>
        <div class="faq-body">Legally, yes — but not every seller follows the law. Wild-caught African Greys are occasionally trafficked into the USA through falsified documents. Always demand CITES documentation and verify the breeder's USDA AWA license number before purchasing. If a seller cannot produce both, walk away.</div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Are captive-bred African Greys better pets than wild-caught?</summary>
        <div class="faq-body">Yes, significantly. Captive-bred hand-raised African Greys are socialized to humans from hatching, making them less fearful, more trainable, and more likely to develop talking ability. Wild-caught birds are traumatized by capture and transport, often never fully tame, and frequently carry diseases that can infect other birds in the household.</div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cta-section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Browse Our Captive-Bred African Greys</h2>
      <p>Every bird we place carries CITES documentation, a DNA sex certificate, an avian vet health certificate, and a written health guarantee.</p>
      <div class="cta-buttons">
        <a href="/congo-african-grey-for-sale/" class="btn-outline">Congo African Greys</a>
        <a href="/timneh-african-grey-for-sale/" class="btn-outline">Timneh African Greys</a>
        <a href="/contact-us/" class="btn-primary">Inquire About Availability</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</main>

</BaseLayout>
